    <h1>The Yellow Duck<br>Phenomenon</h1>
    <span class="subtitle">ways to order</span>
    <span class="author">Lyske Gais</span>
  </div>

  <div class="home-canvas">
    <div class="home-text">

      <div class="home-section"
           data-label="Introducing the Yellow Duck"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/introduction/" | url }}"
           data-text="Every possible avenue of knowledge must be explored, every door tried to see if it is open. No kind of evidence need be left untouched on the score of remoteness or complexity, of minuteness or triviality.">
        Every possible avenue of knowledge must be explored, every door tried to see if it is open. No kind of evidence need be left untouched on the score of remoteness or complexity, of minuteness or triviality. The tendency of modern enquiry is more and more towards the conclusion that if law is anywhere, it is everywhere. E.B. Tylor. Searching for the yellow duck. Thousand words is a book with drawings and words. It is a visual dictionary with as many things and words as possible on a page. Sometimes they are in a setting, a context; some pages are specific topics with separate images/words; and sometimes it is only images or words. This book truly was one of my favourites. All the things in the world were in this book. It was ordered chaos. You could find and make your own stories with it. And one thing you were sure of, was of finding a little yellow duck in every scene. The duck was the fixed thing. You might not see it — the duck had a habit of hiding behind things — but it was always there. You just had to look for it. In the first week of this final year studying for my master, I scanned the covers of all my books. I was hoping to give a bit of insight into my head. This obsessive act gave a glimpse, but did not give the answer. For the thesis I had to go a bit beyond the cover. Instead of going for the multitude and deriving the answers from a large amount of different sources, I decided to concentrate on a few specific texts. One text led to another, and so this thesis follows my research in a chronological way. In a way, this thesis is a search for the yellow duck 2.0. I've been studying at an art academy for six years and now almost at the end of two years master study. It's about time I found the yellow duck in my work, be able to explain the thinking behind my art practice. There is a line in what I do. I can see it, and there are some elements in it I can name. But I can't put my finger on what ties it all together. What is it that I do? In 1956 A.D. Hall and R.E. Fagen write an introductory chapter for a course at Bell Telephone Laboratories. For their text they used a paper, written in 1950 by Ludwig von Bertalanffy, about the General Systems Theory. Ludwig von Bertalanffy developed his theory further and in 1968 published the book General System Theory. This book was published by the same publisher that Jack Burnham had. He picked it up, was inspired by it and in 1968 wrote Systems Aesthetics. This text, printed in Artforum, introduced the systems theory to the 1960s art world. So it is not such a big leap from a scientific text written by mathematicians to the late 1960s art scene.
      </div>

      <div class="home-section"
           data-label="Chapter I — A fixed set of rules"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-1/" | url }}"
           data-text="It seems that rules play an important part in the way I work. A system can be defined as a set of objects together with relationships between the objects and between their attributes.">
        Chapter I — A fixed set of rules. It seems that rules play an important part in the way I work. When I start a work, I usually start with a question, a fascination or a problem. In most cases the solution brings another fixed set of rules in which I work. A system can be defined as a set of objects together with relationships between the objects and between their attributes. Hall and Fagen offer this definition which Ludwig von Bertalanffy adopted in his book. A system consists of objects and the relations between them. The objects can have different attributes. An important element in the definition is that there are relations. There are always at least two elements in a relation. A single object is not yet a system. General Systems Theory is a science that studies the general concept of systems and aims to explain rules and principles that are valid for all types of systems. The aim is to show structural similarities in the different sciences. The idea is that the same kind of logical and mathematical laws apply for systems regardless of the domain of investigation. By seeking these similarities it can also show structural differences and make it possible to see where something from one domain can transfer to another domain. The theory tries to build a bridge between the various disciplines. The main idea of General Systems Theory was to create an all-encompassing science that could cross between different disciplines. A system is defined not alone by the elements of which it consists, but by the relations between these elements. Relations are what make a system, not the parts in isolation.

        <span class="home-image-embed"
              data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
              title="Hans Haacke — Condensation Cube, 1963–65">
          <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/63_65condensationcube2_347x500jpg.jpg" | url }}"
               width="55" height="80" alt="Hans Haacke, Condensation Cube">
          <span class="embed-caption">Haacke</span>
        </span>

        Every system has an environment, the set of all objects a change in whose attributes affect the system. The environment and the system are always linked to each other. Within every system there are subsets that can be seen as systems in themselves: subsystems. These can overlap. An important distinction within systems theory is the one between open and closed systems. Closed systems are isolated from the environment. Open systems exchange matter with the environment, exhibit import and export, building-up and breaking-down of their material components. Most biological systems are open systems. They are in constant exchange with their environment, taking in energy, nutrients and matter, and releasing waste products. The notion of compatibility is used to describe how systems relate to each other. It addresses whether two or more systems can work together without conflict.
      </div>

      <div class="home-section"
           data-label="Chapter II — A fixed set of rules on art"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-2/" | url }}"
           data-text="Burnham introduced Systems Aesthetics to the art world in 1968, connecting von Bertalanffy's general systems theory to contemporary art practice.">
        Chapter II — A fixed set of rules on art. Burnham. In 1968 Jack Burnham published Systems Aesthetics in Artforum. Burnham introduced the systems theory of Ludwig von Bertalanffy to the art world. He saw a fundamental shift happening in art away from the object toward systems. The shift Burnham described was a shift from an object-oriented to a systems-oriented culture. Not the single isolated artwork but the system, the relations between objects and ideas, becomes the subject of art. Conceptual Art had already started to question the primacy of the art object. Artists like Sol LeWitt, Lawrence Weiner and Joseph Kosuth had argued that the idea or concept behind a work is more important than the physical realisation. If the idea is there, the work exists, even without being physically made.

        <span class="home-image-embed"
              data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
              title="Dan Graham — Homes for America, 1966–67">
          <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/grahamhomes6667.jpg" | url }}"
               width="70" height="50" alt="Dan Graham, Homes for America">
          <span class="embed-caption">Graham</span>
        </span>

        Burnham saw the concept of environment as central to understanding this new art. The environment is not just the physical space in which art is displayed but the entire context in which the work is produced and received. The artwork is always part of a larger system. Conceptual Art as a movement was defined by its questioning of the traditional definition of art. If art could be an idea, then the boundaries of what art could be were dramatically expanded. The question became not what something is, but how it functions within a system of relations.
      </div>

      <div class="home-section"
           data-label="Chapter III — Explained by artworks"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
           data-text="System Aesthetic. Burnham's key argument was that the most important art of his time was not concerned with the production of objects but with the production of systems.">
        Chapter III — A fixed set of rules on art, explained by artworks. System Aesthetic. Burnham's key argument was that the most important art of his time was not concerned with the production of objects but with the production of systems. A Transition from an Object-Oriented to a System-Oriented Culture. The shift Burnham saw was happening everywhere in culture. In architecture, urban planning, music, and art, the emphasis was moving from the individual object to the system, from the single thing to the relationships between things. Art Does Not Reside in Material Entities. If art is fundamentally about systems and relationships, then it cannot be located in any single material object. Art is Not Autonomous. Art is always embedded in a context, always part of a larger system of relations. To claim autonomy for art is to misunderstand what art is.

        <span class="home-image-embed"
              data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
              title="Martha Rosler — Bringing the War Home, 1967–72">
          <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/Rosler.jpg" | url }}"
               width="50" height="65" alt="Martha Rosler">
          <span class="embed-caption">Rosler</span>
        </span>

        <span class="home-image-embed"
              data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
              title="Mel Bochner — Measurement Room, 1969">
          <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/Mel_Brochner_measurment_room.jpg" | url }}"
               width="55" height="75" alt="Mel Bochner, Measurement Room">
          <span class="embed-caption">Bochner</span>
        </span>

        <span class="home-image-embed"
              data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
              title="Robert Smithson">
          <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/Smithson.jpg" | url }}"
               width="70" height="50" alt="Robert Smithson">
          <span class="embed-caption">Smithson</span>
        </span>

        Art is Conceptual Focus. What art provides is a specific kind of attention, a way of focusing on particular systems and making them visible. No Definition or Theory of Art Can Be Historically Unvarying. Because art is always embedded in its context and because contexts change, no single definition of art can be valid for all times. Art must be understood historically.
      </div>

      <div class="home-section"
           data-label="Chapter IV — Composition of Thoughts"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-4/" | url }}"
           data-text="The concept of system is what ties together my practice. When I make work, I set up a system — a set of rules, a framework, a structure — and then I follow it.">
        Chapter IV — Composition of Thoughts. Truth. The question of truth in art and in knowledge more broadly is central to my practice. I do not believe in a single truth, but in multiple truths that are always situated, always produced within specific contexts and relations. Unity. A system is unified in the sense that it holds together as a whole, but it is not homogeneous. Unity in diversity: the system holds together precisely because of the differences between its elements. System. The concept of system is what ties together my practice. When I make work, I set up a system — a set of rules, a framework, a structure — and then I follow it. The system is the artwork, not the physical result.

        <span class="home-image-embed"
              data-url="{{ "/projects/stegen-van-harlingen/" | url }}"
              title="Stegen van Harlingen — Lyske Gais">
          <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/Vorm.jpg" | url }}"
               width="45" height="80" alt="Stegen van Harlingen">
          <span class="embed-caption">Vorm</span>
        </span>

        Aesthetic Enjoyment. The aesthetic dimension of the work is not separate from its conceptual dimension. The aesthetic experience is the experience of the system, the experience of the relations between things. Inspiration. Where does inspiration come from? For me, it comes from observation, from looking at the world and finding structures and systems in what I see. Perception. Perception is always structured. We do not see raw data but always already interpreted information, ordered and categorised by our perceptual and cognitive systems.
      </div>

      <div class="home-section"
           data-label="Chapter V — Finding the Yellow Duck"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-5/" | url }}"
           data-text="Structures and systems are everywhere. Orders are what make me see. Research: I think you shouldn't exclude anything — everything can be part of the work.">
        Chapter V — Finding the Yellow Duck. Inspiration (See). Structures and systems are everywhere. What catches my eye and makes something a possible subject of a work is not the actual order. Orders are what make me see. Research (Gather). When researching I think you shouldn't exclude anything, everything can be part of the work. Plan (Order). The only way out is to put it all next to each other and get it all back in line. To order them, and by the order itself see what the main elements are. Execute (Do). When I am making, I fix the system and do it, and do it, and do it again. I don't change during the making, because I think that if you do that you can't really judge the end result.

        <span class="home-image-embed"
              data-url="{{ "/projects/amsterdam/" | url }}"
              title="Amsterdam — Lyske Gais">
          <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/Amsterdam.jpg" | url }}"
               width="50" height="70" alt="Amsterdam overhemd">
          <span class="embed-caption">Amsterdam</span>
        </span>

        Space. Art provides a space — similar to the one provided by language — in which things that cannot otherwise coexist can be juxtaposed. Both leave gaps to be filled by the viewer. The gaps might be different, but the fact that they create this unthinkable space is the same.
      </div>

      <div class="home-section"
           data-label="Concluding That Ducks Never Remain Yellow"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/conclusion/" | url }}"
           data-text="The Yellow Duck is the theory on my art practice. The view I have created will not be permanent. It will change; I will change; the world will change.">
        Concluding That Ducks Never Remain Yellow. The Yellow Duck is thus the theory on my art practice. A phenomenon is something that happens and you can observe it. And having learned from Burnham, this conclusion is tied to the here and now. It is a view I have achieved now, with the knowledge and the works I have created thus far and with a world that is at the beginning of the year 2012. I am aware that the view I have created will not be permanent. It will change; I will change; the world will change. The yellow duck I have found now will not stay yellow, or there can be another yellow duck hidden somewhere. What I try to do is lift some connections up from the web of strings and make them visible for a short time. Sometimes to judge, sometimes just to show and tell and make you realise that the world is bigger and more complicated than we can comprehend in our day-to-day lives. Systems and structures are what tie the world together. There is no truth. And I don't mind.
      </div>

